Title: Architectural Refactoring Roadmap: Addressing Core Issues Identified by AI Analysis
Overview
To proactively identify architectural improvements, this repository was analyzed using Google's Gemini 2.5 Pro. Using a specialized system prompt, the model was tasked with evaluating the codebase for architectural issues, generating 12 independent analysis reports.
This issue represents the consolidated findings from all 12 reports. The analysis revealed a strong consensus on a few key areas for improvement.

Detailed Analysis of Issue # 01: Monolithic and Duplicated Data Loading Logic
This report provides a more comprehensive breakdown of the highest-priority architectural issue identified by the AI analysis of the ccusage codebase. This issue was unanimously flagged across all 12 generated reports as the most critical area for refactoring.
1. In-Depth Problem Analysis
The core problem is a systemic violation of two fundamental software design principles: Don't Repeat Yourself (DRY) and the Single Responsibility Principle (SRP). This manifests in the data loading and processing functions.
A. Violation of Don't Repeat Yourself (DRY)
The same complex sequence of operations is implemented multiple times, with only minor variations. This duplicated logic is present in:

src/data-loader.ts

loadDailyUsageData
loadSessionData
loadSessionBlockData


src/_live-monitor.ts

LiveMonitor.getActiveBlock



The repeated sequence of tasks in each of these functions includes:

Discovering Claude configuration directories (getClaudePaths).
Finding all relevant .jsonl files using glob.
Sorting the discovered files chronologically (sortFilesByTimestamp).
Initializing a PricingFetcher instance.
Iterating through each file.
Reading the file content and splitting it into lines.
Iterating through each line, parsing it as JSON.
Validating the parsed data against the usageDataSchema (Zod schema).
Calculating a unique hash for deduplication.
Checking a Set of processed hashes to skip duplicates.
Calculating the cost for the entry (calculateCostForEntry).
Appending the processed entry to an in-memory array (allEntries).

This represents a significant amount of complex, critical code that has been copied and pasted, leading to a brittle and hard-to-maintain system.
B. Violation of the Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)
The data loading functions are monolithic "god functions" that are responsible for far too many distinct tasks. For example, loadDailyUsageData is responsible for:

Low-Level Data Access: File system discovery, globbing, reading files, handling I/O errors.
Data Parsing & Validation: JSON parsing, Zod schema validation.
Data Enrichment: Orchestrating cost calculations via the PricingFetcher.
Data Deduplication: Managing a set of unique hashes.
High-Level Business Logic: Aggregating the final list of entries into daily summaries.

This tight coupling of low-level infrastructure concerns with high-level business logic is a classic SRP violation. The function has multiple reasons to change, making it fragile.
2. Tangible Negative Impacts
The current architecture has several direct negative consequences:

High Maintenance Overhead: A simple change to the file parsing, deduplication logic, or error handling must be identified and meticulously replicated across at least four different locations. This is time-consuming and inefficient.
Increased Risk of Bugs: Manually replicating logic is highly error-prone. It's easy for a bug fix to be applied in one function but missed in another, leading to inconsistent behavior and difficult-to-diagnose bugs.
Poor Testability: It is nearly impossible to unit test the aggregation logic (e.g., "does this correctly group entries by day?") in isolation. Any test of the aggregation logic is forced to be an integration test that also involves the filesystem, file parsing, and cost calculation dependencies, making tests slow and complex to set up.
Impeded Future Development: Adding a new report type (e.g., a "Weekly Report") would require copying and pasting one of the large load... functions yet again, further compounding the technical debt.
Reduced Code Clarity: The monolithic nature of these functions makes them difficult to read and understand. A developer must hold the entire complex pipeline in their head at once, rather than reasoning about smaller, self-contained units of logic.

3. Detailed Refactoring Recommendation: A Layered Streaming Pipeline
The consensus recommendation is to refactor the entire data pipeline into a layered, stream-based architecture. This establishes a clear separation of concerns.
Layer 1: The Data Access Layer (streamUsageEntries)
Create a single, central asynchronous generator function responsible for the entire data extraction and preparation pipeline.

Signature: async function* streamUsageEntries(options: LoadOptions): AsyncIterable<LoadedUsageEntry>
Single Responsibility: Its only job is to discover, read, parse, validate, enrich, and yield a canonical LoadedUsageEntry object one by one.
Encapsulated Logic: This function would encapsulate all the common logic listed in the DRY violation section above: path discovery, globbing, sorting, file I/O, parsing, validation, deduplication, and cost calculation.
Benefit: This creates a single source of truth for how data is acquired from the filesystem.

Layer 2: The Aggregation Layer (Strategies)
Create a set of pure functions or classes whose sole responsibility is to consume the stream from Layer 1 and aggregate the data. This aligns perfectly with the Strategy Pattern.

Example: A class DailyAggregator would have a method like aggregate(stream: AsyncIterable<LoadedUsageEntry>).
Logic: It would iterate over the stream (for await...of) and build up its daily summary map. It would only hold the aggregated data in memory, not the millions of individual entries.
Benefit: The aggregation logic is completely decoupled from the data source and can be unit-tested easily with a mock stream of LoadedUsageEntry objects.

4. "Before" and "After" Code Structure
Before (Simplified Pseudo-code):
// in data-loader.ts
export async function loadDailyUsageData(options) {
  const claudePaths = getClaudePaths();
  const allFiles = await glob(claudePaths);
  const sortedFiles = await sortFilesByTimestamp(allFiles);
  const fetcher = new PricingFetcher();
  const allEntries = [];
  const processedHashes = new Set();

  for (const file of sortedFiles) {
    const content = await readFile(file);
    for (const line of content.split('\n')) {
      // --> DUPLICATED LOGIC START
      const data = JSON.parse(line);
      if (!isValid(data)) continue;

      const hash = createUniqueHash(data);
      if (processedHashes.has(hash)) continue;
      processedHashes.add(hash);

      const cost = await calculateCostForEntry(data, options.mode, fetcher);
      allEntries.push({ ...data, cost });
      // --> DUPLICATED LOGIC END
    }
  }

  // Aggregation logic here...
  const groupedByDate = groupBy(allEntries, ...);
  return processGroups(groupedByDate);
}
After (Simplified Pseudo-code):
// NEW Central Data Source
async function* streamUsageEntries(options) {
  const claudePaths = getClaudePaths();
  const allFiles = await glob(claudePaths);
  const sortedFiles = await sortFilesByTimestamp(allFiles);
  using fetcher = new PricingFetcher();
  const processedHashes = new Set();

  for (const file of sortedFiles) {
    const content = await readFile(file);
    for (const line of content.split('\n')) {
      // Centralized logic is now only here
      const data = JSON.parse(line);
      if (!isValid(data)) continue;
      const hash = createUniqueHash(data);
      if (processedHashes.has(hash)) continue;
      processedHashes.add(hash);
      const cost = await calculateCostForEntry(data, options.mode, fetcher);

      // Yield a fully processed entry
      yield { ...data, cost };
    }
  }
}

// REFACTORED Loader/Aggregator
export async function loadDailyUsageData(options) {
  const entryStream = streamUsageEntries(options);
  const dailyTotals = new Map<string, DailySummary>();

  for await (const entry of entryStream) {
    const date = entry.timestamp.substring(0, 10);
    // Pure aggregation logic
    const summary = dailyTotals.get(date) ?? createEmptySummary();
    summary.totalTokens += entry.tokens;
    summary.totalCost += entry.cost;
    dailyTotals.set(date, summary);
  }

  return Array.from(dailyTotals.values());
}
5. Summary of Benefits
This refactoring is foundational. It directly leads to:

High Maintainability: The complex data pipeline logic exists in exactly one place. Fixes and enhancements are simple and safe.
Excellent Testability: The streamUsageEntries generator and the individual aggregator strategies can be unit-tested in complete isolation.
Extensibility: Adding a new report type becomes trivial: simply create a new aggregator class/function that consumes the stream. No boilerplate code needs to be duplicated.
Improved Clarity: The responsibilities of each part of the system become clear, making the codebase easier for new and existing contributors to understand.
Foundation for Performance: A streaming pipeline is a prerequisite for solving the memory scalability issues, as it avoids loading the entire dataset into memory.


Next Steps
This is obviously a massive amount of information. I don't expect immediate action on all of these points. My hope is that this analysis can serve as a valuable resource for future development and refactoring efforts.
Thanks for building such an interesting project.

