Bug: Incorrect day grouping when user's timezone differs from UTC
Summary
When running ccusage, usage data is incorrectly grouped by day for users whose local timezone differs from UTC. For example, API calls made at 8:08 PM PST are being grouped into the next day instead of the current day.
Steps to Reproduce

Be in a timezone other than UTC (e.g., PST/UTC-8, EST/UTC-5)
Make Claude API calls in the evening (after 4 PM PST, 7 PM EST, etc.)
Run ccusage daily
Observe that evening usage appears under the next day's date

Expected Behavior
Usage should be grouped by the user's local date. If I make an API call at 8:08 PM PST on January 24th, it should appear under January 24th in the daily report.
Actual Behavior
Usage is being grouped by UTC date. An API call at 8:08 PM PST on January 24th (which is 4:08 AM UTC on January 25th) appears under January 25th in the daily report.
Root Cause Analysis
The issue is in the formatDateInternal function in src/data-loader.ts. The function detects timezone indicators in timestamps and uses UTC date components when they're present:
// Current implementation (line 471-477)
const hasTimezone = /Z|[+-]\d{2}:\d{2}/.test(dateStr);

// Use UTC getters if timezone is specified, otherwise use local getters
const year = hasTimezone ? date.getUTCFullYear() : date.getFullYear();
const month = String(hasTimezone ? date.getUTCMonth() + 1 : date.getMonth() + 1).padStart(2, '0');
const day = String(hasTimezone ? date.getUTCDate() : date.getDate()).padStart(2, '0');
Since Claude's JSONL files store timestamps with the 'Z' suffix (e.g., 2025-07-17T04:19:45.213Z), the function always uses UTC components for date extraction, causing incorrect grouping for non-UTC users.
Recommended Fix
Modify formatDateInternal to always use local timezone for date grouping:
// Recommended fix
function formatDateInternal(dateStr: string, twoLine: boolean): string {
	const date = new Date(dateStr);

	// Always use local timezone for date grouping
	// This ensures usage is grouped by the user's local day, not UTC day
	const year = date.getFullYear();
	const month = String(date.getMonth() + 1).padStart(2, '0');
	const day = String(date.getDate()).padStart(2, '0');

	return twoLine ? `${year}\n${month}-${day}` : `${year}-${month}-${day}`;
}
Why This Fix Works

The JavaScript Date constructor automatically converts UTC timestamps to the user's local timezone
By using getFullYear(), getMonth(), and getDate() (instead of their UTC variants), we get the date components in the user's local timezone
This ensures usage is grouped by the day it occurred in the user's timezone, not UTC

Impact
This bug affects:

All users not in UTC timezone - The further from UTC, the more hours of the day are affected
Evening usage tracking - API calls made in the evening appear on the wrong day
Daily quota management - Users may think they've exceeded quotas on the wrong day
Billing accuracy - For users tracking costs by day, the data is misaligned

Affected Timezones Examples

PST (UTC-8): Usage after 4 PM appears on next day
EST (UTC-5): Usage after 7 PM appears on next day
JST (UTC+9): Usage before 9 AM appears on previous day
AEST (UTC+10): Usage before 10 AM appears on previous day

Test Updates Required
The fix requires updating tests to expect local timezone behavior:
// Old test expecting UTC behavior
it('formats UTC timestamps using UTC date', () => {
    expect(formatDate('2024-01-01T00:00:00Z')).toBe('2024-01-01');
});

// New test expecting local timezone behavior
it('formats UTC timestamps using local date', () => {
    const utcDate = new Date('2024-01-01T00:00:00Z');
    const expected = `${utcDate.getFullYear()}-${String(utcDate.getMonth() + 1).padStart(2, '0')}-${String(utcDate.getDate()).padStart(2, '0')}`;
    expect(formatDate('2024-01-01T00:00:00Z')).toBe(expected);
});
Additional Context

The current behavior is technically correct from a data storage perspective (UTC timestamps are standard)
However, for a usage tracking tool, local timezone grouping is more intuitive and matches user expectations
This change only affects display/grouping logic, not the underlying data storage
The JSON output format documentation already mentions that ISO timestamps are used for machine parsing

Workaround
Until this is fixed, users can mentally adjust the day grouping based on their timezone offset, but this is error-prone and inconvenient.

